flowRoot.flowPara: CompositeUnit and OrUnit both contain multiple embedded pattern units. CompositeUnit tries to match them to consecutive substrings while OrUnit tries to match all subunits to substrings starting at the same position. The addModifier function is overridden as it needs to be propagated to embedded units. As the order in which addUnit and addModifier are called should not have any effect, its important that PatternUnit::modifiers is a set.

SequenceUnit is mainly responsible for choosing the fastest algorithm (object composition) based on the modifiers. If no modifiers are present, the KMP algorithm is chosen. If an edit-distance is given, the TNFA or the bitap algorithms are chosen. If a large number of edits are allowed, the TNFA algorithm is chosen and given a low number of edits the backtrack algorithm is chosen.
A pattern unit match specified by the position and length of the substring and the number of edits used to match the pattern unit to the substring (only for reporting).
Following is an object-diagram of the pattern "p1=AAATC/1 (~p1 | <p1)/1,0 p2=.{2,} 3..3 ~p2"

It could be implementationally convenient if the EditModifier which is applied to the OrUnit got inherited by the two ReferenceUnits. The PalindromeUnit allows O(n)-time detection of palindromes which, unlike any pattern units defined in the readme, are represented by multiple units in the original pattern.
